**Description**; The previous code converted both states to density matrices, which is both inefficient and numerically inaccurate. We propose to use the reduced fidelity formula for pure states, given by the modulus of their inner product. **Related issues or PRs**; Related to #361 and #925. Reusing @lucainnocenti example (https://github.com/qutip/qutip/issues/925#issuecomment-542318121):; ```python; import qutip as qt; import numpy as np. A = qt.Qobj(np.array([; 0.867314655330313 - 0.4576338188944636j,; 0.17267952805615244 - 0.09111291375544905j,; 0.013020232894921149 -0.006875138252288391j; ])); B = qt.Qobj(np.array([; 0.9806443568092577, 0.19524328915024022, 0.014720852555238875; ])). fid1 = np.abs(np.vdot(A.full(), B.full())); fid2 = np.abs((A.dag() * B)[0, 0]); fid3 = np.abs(A.overlap(B)); fid_qt = qt.fidelity(A, B); print(f'Correct:
{fid1}
{fid2}
{fid3}'); print(f'Incorrect:
{fid_qt}'); ```; ```; Correct:; 0.9999999999849929; 0.9999999999849929; 0.9999999999849929; Incorrect:; 1.0000000028441378; ```. Note that this PR does not fix the proposition from @lucainnocenti https://github.com/qutip/qutip/issues/925#issuecomment-542318121 to perform the general computation using `scipy.linalg.svdvals` at the cost of computing the square root of both matrices.
